## Government services

### Police

The [North End](/North_End,_Boston) falls under the jurisdiction of the [Boston Police Department](/Boston_Police_Department)'s A-1 district, a rather expansive territory that also encompasses the bustling areas of Downtown, [Beacon Hill](/Beacon_Hill,_Boston), and [Chinatown](/Chinatown,_Boston). [36]

Residents often voice their complaints regarding persistent issues of noise and litter, largely stemming from what they perceive as excessive partying within the neighborhood. In response, in 2012, [Boston](/Boston) police officers predictably increased patrols in the [North End](/North_End,_Boston) to address these noise complaints, a classic reactive measure. [37] Other areas of concern have, unfortunately, included a series of attacks on women and a spate of breaking and enterings targeting residential apartments, reminding one that even historic charm doesn't deter all forms of human depravity. [38] [39] [40] Historically, members of the infamous [Patriarca crime family](/Patriarca_crime_family) have either resided in or operated out of the [North End](/North_End,_Boston), including figures such as [Gennaro Angiulo](/Gennaro_Angiulo), [Gaspare Messina](/Gaspare_Messina), and the notorious Dinunzio brothers (Anthony & Carmen), adding a darker, more organized layer to the neighborhood's intricate history. [41]

### Fire

The [North End](/North_End,_Boston) is diligently served by the [Boston Fire Department](/Boston_Fire_Department), an organization with a long and storied history in a city prone to conflagrations. The area has, regrettably, been impacted by a number of significant fires throughout its existence, a grim reminder of the destructive power of uncontrolled flame. The Boston Fire Historical Society meticulously notes the following five-alarm fires that have ravaged the [North End](/North_End,_Boston) since 1860, each a scar on the urban landscape: [42]

*   December 10, 1905 – The [Consolidated Gas Company](/Consolidated_Gas_Company) coal sheds on [Commercial Street](/Commercial_Street_(Boston)) opposite Charter Street, a blaze of industrial scale.
*   February 20, 1913 – Braman, Dow & Company at 239 Causeway Street.
*   November 2, 1952 – [Union Wharf](/Union_Wharf) off [Commercial Street](/Commercial_Street_(Boston)), a waterfront inferno.
*   March 7, 1962 – Commercial Wharf, another maritime tragedy.
*   July 20, 1978 – An apartment building at 179–181 Salem Street, a heartbreaking loss of homes.
*   February 22, 2007 – A five-story commercial and residential building at 129 Endicott Street, a more recent reminder of the ever-present danger.

Tragically, two of these fires are known to have resulted in at least 10 fatalities each, both grimly involving crowded housing conditions, a recurring societal failure:

*   February 2, 1890 – A devastating tenement fire at 259 North Street, claiming 12 lives. [43] [44]
*   January 29, 1902 – A lodging house fire at 12 Fleet Street, resulting in 10 deaths. [45] [46]

### Public education

The [Boston Public School system](/Boston_Public_Schools) oversees the operation of the John Eliot Elementary School, a venerable institution located right in the [North End](/North_End,_Boston). This school, with an impressive lineage, first opened its doors as the North Writing School in 1713 and later merged with the North Latin School in 1790 to form the John Eliot School. It proudly holds the distinction of being [Boston](/Boston)'s oldest continuously run school, a testament to its enduring commitment to education. In 2007, the Eliot school faced the rather uncomfortable prospect of closure due to what was deemed "poor performance." However, between 2007 and 2011, dedicated school administrators instituted a remarkably successful improvement program. By 2012, the Eliot school had not only turned its fortunes around but was officially classified as an "innovation school," earning well-deserved recognition for excellence from Governor [Deval Patrick](/Deval_Patrick). A rare instance of positive bureaucratic intervention. [47] [48]

### Public library

The [Boston Public Library](/Boston_Public_Library) maintains and operates the North End Branch Library, a vital community resource located at 25 Parmenter Street. This branch was originally established in 1913 and subsequently relocated to its current premises, a building thoughtfully designed by the architect [Carl Koch](/Carl_Koch_(architect)), in 1963. This particular branch distinguishes itself by maintaining a dedicated Italian-language collection, a fitting tribute to the neighborhood's heritage, as well as a local history collection, in addition to its standard holdings, catering to the diverse informational needs of its patrons. [32] [49]

## Public transportation

The [North End](/North_End,_Boston) is, thankfully, quite accessible via the extensive mass transit network provided by the [Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority](/Massachusetts_Bay_Transportation_Authority) (MBTA), offering various options for navigating the city's labyrinthine streets, a necessary evil for any urban dweller. These options include:

*   **[MBTA subway](/MBTA_subway):** The [Orange Line](/Orange_Line_(MBTA)) and [Green Line](/Green_Line_(MBTA)) are accessible at the nearby [Haymarket](/Haymarket_station_(MBTA)) and [North Station](/North_Station_(subway)) stops, providing crucial connections. The [Blue Line](/Blue_Line_(MBTA)) is also within reach at [Aquarium station](/Aquarium_(MBTA_station)), offering a direct link to [East Boston](/East_Boston) and [Logan International Airport](/Logan_International_Airport).
*   **[MBTA Commuter Rail](/MBTA_Commuter_Rail):** Four commuter rail lines originate or terminate at [North Station](/North_Station), connecting the [North End](/North_End,_Boston) to outlying suburbs, for those who prefer to escape the city's embrace.
*   **[MBTA bus](/MBTA_bus):** A comprehensive network of bus lines serves the area, including routes 4, 92, 93, 111, 191, 192, 193, 325, 326, 352, 354, 424, 426, 426/455, and 428. Notably, the number 4 bus utilizes [Commercial Street](/Commercial_Street_(Boston)) for a portion of its route, efficiently connecting [North Station](/North_Station) with [South Station](/South_Station), a rather convenient cross-city link.
*   **[MBTA ferry](/MBTA_ferry):** For a more scenic, albeit less frequent, mode of transport, ferries depart from [Long Wharf](/Long_Wharf_(Boston)) and Central Wharf, offering connections across [Boston Harbor](/Boston_Harbor).

## Infrastructure

**View of buildings on Garden Court Street:** A narrow thoroughfare, characteristic of the [North End](/North_End,_Boston)'s dense, historic urban fabric.

The [North End](/North_End,_Boston) is characterized by its notoriously narrow, densely packed streets, a charming anachronism in a modern city, but also a logistical headache. No major thoroughfares cut directly through the neighborhood, which means that virtually all trips made *within* the neighborhood are, by necessity, accomplished by walking, a simple truth in a complex world. Still, many sidewalks are unfortunately not [ADA](/Americans_with_Disabilities_Act_of_1990) accessible, primarily due to their inherent narrowness or frequent obstructions. Rectifying this accessibility issue would, predictably, necessitate the removal of some precious on-street parking spaces, a trade-off that rarely pleases everyone.

The current system of free and unlimited resident parking passes is, in a word, absurd: 4,000 permits are issued for a mere 1,500 available on-street resident parking spaces. [50] A perfect microcosm of human ambition exceeding available resources, wouldn't you say? The few visitor parking spaces, lacking meters, are nonetheless constrained by a two-hour limit, a small mercy. For those willing to pay, public parking is available within the neighborhood at Lewis Wharf, Sargents Wharf, and the Cooper Street lot. Nearby public parking garages, offering more substantial capacity, include [Government Center](/Government_Center,_Boston), Dock Square, and the Boston Harbor Garage. At night, many of the ubiquitous restaurants offer valet parking, a convenient, if often overpriced, solution to the perennial parking dilemma.

Busy roads, like arterial blood vessels, encircle the [North End](/North_End,_Boston). [Commercial Street](/Commercial_Street_(Boston)) features two lanes of northbound and one lane of southbound traffic, and gracefully arcs around the [North End](/North_End,_Boston)'s eastern perimeter, a constant hum of movement. [51] Private shuttles, linking [North Station](/North_Station) to the burgeoning [Seaport neighborhood](/Seaport_District), also make use of this road. On the western edge lies [North Washington Street](/Washington_Street_(Boston)), which, perhaps unsurprisingly, carries the highest traffic volume in the immediate area, a testament to urban congestion. [52]

Seasonal private ferries, serving the picturesque [Boston Harbor Islands National Recreation Area](/Boston_Harbor_Islands_National_Recreation_Area), operate from [Long Wharf](/Long_Wharf_(Boston)). For those seeking a more bespoke maritime experience, Boston Water Taxis provides seasonal, on-demand water taxi service from five convenient [North End](/North_End,_Boston) docks: [Long Wharf](/Long_Wharf_(Boston)), Yacht Haven Marina, Sargents Wharf, Burroughs Wharf, and Battery Wharf, offering a unique perspective on the city. [53]

In 2017, the City of [Boston](/Boston) unveiled a two-way protected cycle track on the east side of [Commercial Street](/Commercial_Street_(Boston)), a thoughtful, if belated, concession to the increasing number of urban cyclists. [54] Three [BLUEBikes](/Blue_Bikes) (formerly Hubway) bikeshare stations are strategically placed on the edges of the neighborhood: at Commercial and Fleet Streets, [Hanover](/Hanover_Street_(Boston)) and Cross Streets, and [Atlantic Avenue](/Atlantic_Avenue_(Boston)) and [Long Wharf](/Long_Wharf_(Boston)), encouraging a more active mode of transport. [55]

